<section xml:id="sec_the_integration_methods_tutor">
  <title>The Integration Methods Tutor</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
          <idx><h>integral</h><h>integration methods tutor</h></idx>
    </p>
    <p>
      The Integration Methods tutor can be used to evaluate an integral step-by-step.
      You can either manually attempt different techniques on the integral,
      or let Maple decide which techniques to use.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>Opening up the Integration Methods tutor using menus.</caption>
      \adjincludegraphics[width=\textwidth]{tutorials/figures/IntTutorLoad1-eps-converted-to.pdf}
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <caption>Opening up the Integration Methods tutor using commands. The <c>Student[Calculus1]</c> package is required.</caption>
      \adjincludegraphics[width=\textwidth]{tutorials/figures/IntTutorLoad2-eps-converted-to.pdf}
    </figure>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Evaluating <m>\displaystyle\int x^2e^x</m> Using Integration by Parts</title>
    <p>
          <idx><h>integral</h><h>integration methods tutor</h></idx>
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>If the Get Hint button is clicked, Maple will suggest an integration technique.</caption>
      \adjincludegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,trim={0 {0.2\height} 0 0},clip]{tutorials/figures/IntTutorQ1-1-eps-converted-to.pdf}
    </figure>
    <aside>
      <p>
        When typing out the function in the tutor,
        you will not have access to the palettes toolbar in Maple.
        You will need to type out commands such as <c>sqrt()</c> for square roots.
        You must also include the symbol * for multiplication.
      </p>
    </aside>
    <figure>
      <caption>Integration by parts  can be applied to integrals of the form <m>\int u\ dv</m>, where <m>u=f(x)</m> and <m>dv = g'(x) dx</m>.</caption>
      <image width="60%" source="images/IntTutorQ1-2-eps-converted-to.png"/>
      \adjincludegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,trim={0 {0.5\height} 0 0},clip]{tutorials/figures/IntTutorQ1-3-eps-converted-to.pdf}
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <caption>Using the constant multiple rule, integration by parts a second time, and the exponential rule to evaluate the integral.</caption>
      \adjincludegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,trim={0 {0.2\height} 0 0},clip]{tutorials/figures/IntTutorQ1-4-eps-converted-to.pdf}
      <image width="60%" source="images/IntTutorQ1-5-eps-converted-to.png"/>
      \adjincludegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,trim={0 {0.2\height} 0 0},clip]{tutorials/figures/IntTutorQ1-6-eps-converted-to.pdf}
    </figure>
  </subsection>
